[{"id":"VR930924","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">Show all your work for each part of the question. The parts within the question may not have equal weight.</p><br/><div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<p class=\"standalone_statement style:2\">In the Bohr model of a single-electron atom, an electron moves along circular orbits around a nucleus that has mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"m sub p\"><math alttext=\"m sub p\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>m</mi><mi>p</mi></msub></math></span></span> and positive charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive lowercase e\"><math alttext=\"positive lowercase e\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>+</mo><mi>e</mi></math></span></span>. The electron has mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"m sub lowercase e\"><math alttext=\"m sub lowercase e\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>m</mi><mi>e</mi></msub></math></span></span> and negative charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"negative lowercase e\"><math alttext=\"negative lowercase e\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>-</mo><mi>e</mi></math></span></span>.</p>\n<div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 1Â shows an energy level diagram of an atom. The left side of the diagram is labeled Energy and the right side of the right side is labeled State. The diagram has three levels. The top level is n equals 3 and is labeled negative 1.5 electron volts. The second level is n equals 2 and is labeled negative 3.4 electron volts. The third level is n equals 1 and is labeled negative 13.6 electron volts.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR930924.g04.svg\"/></div>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> represents three discrete energy states and their corresponding energies for the atom.</p>\n</div></div>\n</div></div><div class=\"item_part part_id:A part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"A\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Draw</span> arrows on Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> to represent all possible atomic transitions between the states shown that could result in the emission of a photon.</p></div>\n"},{"id":"VR930924","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) The electron orbits the nucleus at radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r sub 1\"><math alttext=\"r sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span> when the atom is in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n equals 1\"><math alttext=\"n equals 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> state.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Derive</span> an expression for the total energy <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase E sub 1\"><math alttext=\"uppercase E sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span> of the atom when the atom is in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n equals 1\"><math alttext=\"n equals 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> state. Express your answer in terms of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase e\"><math alttext=\"lowercase e\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>e</mi></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r sub 1\"><math alttext=\"r sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>, and physical constants, as appropriate. Begin your derivation by writing a fundamental physics principle or an equation from the reference information.</p></div>\n"},{"id":"VR930924","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:C part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"C\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c) In the classical model of an atom, it was assumed that an electron could orbit the nucleus at any radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r\"><math alttext=\"r\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>r</mi></math></span></span>.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">On Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, based on the classical model, <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">sketch</span> the total energy <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase E\"><math alttext=\"uppercase E\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>E</mi></math></span></span> of the atom as a function of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r\"><math alttext=\"r\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>r</mi></math></span></span>.</p><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 2 shows the first and fourth quadrant of a coordinate plane. The horizontal axis is labeled r and the vertical axis is labeled uppercase E. The origin is labeled with an O.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR930924.g05.svg\"/></div></div>\n"},{"id":"VR930924","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:D part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"D\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(d) Consider the Bohr model of the atom and the states shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>. The electron orbits the nucleus at radii <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r sub 2\"><math alttext=\"r sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r sub 3\"><math alttext=\"r sub 3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></span></span> when the atom is in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n equals 2\"><math alttext=\"n equals 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n equals 3\"><math alttext=\"n equals 3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math></span></span> states, respectively.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Indicate</span> whether <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r sub 3\"><math alttext=\"r sub 3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></span></span> is greater than, less than, or equal to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r sub 2\"><math alttext=\"r sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span>. Briefly <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">justify</span> your answer by using at least one feature of the representation from part (a) with your derivation from part (b) or directly from your graph from part (c).</p></div>\n"}]